Ve-FQtAu4alcOGY_qgbXnzDaTZ5fReCWg==\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Thinking about initialization issues**\\n\\nI’m trying to understand why something isn’t covered. It could be that the static field is already initialized by previous tests, which might limit its accessibility for the current context. It's interesting to think about how earlier setups affect new tests. Maybe I need to dig deeper into the initialization process to figure this out. It's a tricky situation, but I’m curious to explore the reasons behind it!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating test coverage issues**\\n\\nI’m trying to unravel why our LogoTest didn’t seem to cover certain elements. It looks like the call site is null unless the TestRunnerTest's Swing logo has run before LogoTest. The static field in Logo should only affect its context, but there’s so much complexity around when the AwtuiTestRunner creates the UI. Maybe tests are failing due to a headless environment causing NullPointer exceptions. I need to double-check if the constructor isn't waiting correctly, perhaps linked to the MediaTracker. It's like a puzzle!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing coverage instrumentation**\\n\\nI’m pondering the coverage instrumentation issues we're facing. If AwtuiTestRunnerTest ran first, the call site might not have been reached in our test, yet it should be covered unless the previous report had the Awtui TestRunner as inactive. Noticing that it reported \\\"newly covered none\\\" hints that the test didn't hit dynamic access, likely due to JUnit's order. I’m also considering if the createUI fails because of the headless environment. Perhaps, metadata isn’t being tracked because prior tests aren’t included. I need to refine this understanding further!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring coverage counts**\\n\\nI'm trying to figure out the coverage counts for call sites globally. It should be covered, but if the test order in the same JVM means the synthetic class$ call site executes just once, that complicates things. If it's mapped to junit.awtui.TestRunner, the report might be considered active. But I’m wondering about the dynamic report per class—shouldn’t it count call sites regardless? Maybe the previous AwtuiTestRunnerTest runs before the active targeted report, but the call wasn't reached due to a test failure? I need to clarify this!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating image loading issues**\\n\\nI’m wondering if the test failed because the `Toolkit.getDefaultToolkit` throws an `AWTError` in the native layer. The `loadImage` method catches `Exception`, not `Error`, which might be why the test didn't pass. However, there’s an indication that the external part isn’t newly covered, so it may not necessarily lead to a failure. I need to ensure that the call is properly handled and investigate further.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring class loading for tests**\\n\\nI'm considering how to reach a static field in a class while it's null. I can't use reflection directly in tests unless necessary for a public API, and I also can't reset static fields with reflection. I wonder if isolating logic in a custom ClassLoader might help, but dynamic class loading seems unsupported after a native build. \\n\\nI need to handle potential errors if unsupported and also prevent other tests from initializing prematurely. I might need to think about class name order and JUnit's alphabetical execution!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing test execution order**\\n\\nI'm thinking about how the existing `AwtuiTestRunnerTest` starts with test A before `LogoTest` runs, which might initialize a static field. If that happens successfully, the class$ may not be reached during the `LogoTest`. I wonder if coverage mapping for dynamic access requires a dedicated file, as the existing coverage might be tied to `TestRunner`.\\n\\nCould the test fail in headless mode, leading to suite aborts? If the report is generated but doesn't include coverage, that suggests the static field in `AwtuiTestRunnerTest` initialized incorrectly and affected the `LogoTest`. The JVM's reuse across tests might be causing this!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering test class structure**\\n\\nI’m thinking that maybe the dynamic report only ran `LogoTest`, but I'm not entirely sure. One solution could be to rename the test class to `AaaLogoTest` to ensure a dedicated file with a one-to-one mapping. The file name should remain `LogoTest`, though. If I can't decide, it seems like the dynamic-access class is likely linked to `LogoTest`. I might consider using `@TestMethodOrder`, but I don’t want to mix up different classes in that setup.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Figuring out class order**\\n\\nI need the logo before Awtui, so I’m thinking about using ClassOrderer.OrderAnnotation to annotate LogoTest with @Order(1). I wonder if I should apply this to other classes as a default too? But if I order all classes, it might affect those without @Order annotations. That seems a bit broad. Maybe it’s better to limit it to @TestClassOrder just for nested classes, not across top-level elements.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_VEKDIKjlSg8vxnmxyBUhJwVS|fc_0d42836eebd4524b0169f91c351c548195aab1704855db51f5", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find tests/src/junit/junit/3.7/src/test/resources -type f -maxdepth 5 -print -exec basename {} \\; && rg -n \"junit.jupiter.testclass.order|ClassOrderer|@Order\" tests/src/junit/junit/3.7 tests/src -S | head -50", "timeout": 10}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 2264, "output": 2061, "cacheRead": 26112, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 30437, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777933335439, "responseId": "resp_0d42836eebd4524b0169f9